Schizophrenia is a severe psychopathology that is defined by a spectrum of symptoms, some of which include delusions, hallucinations, abnormal thinking, and emotional flatness. Schizophrenia is a major cause of disability. Typically manifesting in one's late teenage years or early adult years, schizophrenia symptoms might include, but are not limited to the following: Positive symptoms include hallucinations, delusions, and disordered thinking, all of which include the existence of aberrant experiences or beliefs that are not founded in reality. Hallucinations are the most common kind of positive symptom. Negative symptoms include a lack of typical emotional or behavioral reactions, such as sadness, a lack of desire, and trouble feeling pleasure. These symptoms are characterized by an emotional flatness. Antipsychotic drugs are one kind of pharmacological therapy for schizophrenia. These medications, which are aimed to lessen the positive symptoms of the condition, are called atypical antipsychotics. These drugs are effective because they target certain neurotransmitters and receptor types in the brain. Some of these neurotransmitters include dopamine and serotonin. Typical antipsychotics and atypical antipsychotics are the two categories that exist within the larger category of antipsychotic drugs. Traditional antipsychotic medications, such as haloperidol and chlorpromazine, block the dopamine D2 receptor. They are effective in reducing positive symptoms, such as hallucinations and delusions, but they frequently produce severe side effects, such as extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS), which include tremors, stiffness, and restlessness. Atypical antipsychotics, which include clozapine, risperidone, and olanzapine, have a lower risk of extended-release psychosis (EPS) and a better side-effect profile. However, in addition to targeting serotonin receptors and being effective in reducing negative symptoms, these antipsychotics also target other receptors, such as dopamine receptors. Schizophrenia is a complicated illness, and it is probable that a number of different things contributed to the development of the illness. Heritability, often known as the extent to which a condition is determined by a person's genes, is thought to be somewhere around 80%. There are a number of genetic variants that have been linked to an increased chance of developing schizophrenia. These genetic variations include polymorphisms in genes that are involved in neurotransmission and the development of the brain. In addition, research has shown that persons who have schizophrenia often have structural and functional changes in areas of the brain that are involved in perception, attention, and emotion. These regions include the prefrontal cortex, the hippocampus, and the amygdala, respectively. These disparities point to the possibility that there are anomalies in the neural circuits that link these different parts of the brain. For instance, research conducted using imaging methods like as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) discovered that patients with schizophrenia tend to have lower quantities of gray matter in the prefrontal cortex and the hippocampus. This was discovered via the use of animal models. In addition, research using functional MRI have shown that persons who have schizophrenia often have aberrant activity in the prefrontal cortex. This region of the brain is known to be important in decision-making as well as working memory and attention. Overall, schizophrenia is a significant psychopathology that is defined by a spectrum of symptoms, including delusions, hallucinations, abnormal thinking, and emotional flatness. These symptoms may be seen in people who have schizophrenia. The majority of patients are treated with antipsychotic drugs, which are designed to target certain kinds of neurotransmitters and receptors in the brain. Researchers have uncovered structural and functional changes in brain areas that are involved in perception, attention, and emotion in patients with schizophrenia. It is believed that the condition is caused by a mix of inherited and environmental factors. 